  "overall_strengths": [
    "Strong breadth. MobSF covers app manifest, decompiled source, network security config, certificates, resource strings, and native library hardening in one report.",
    "Manifest and network-security checks are reasonably reliable because they are parser-backed, not just regex backed.",
    "Good for Android platform misconfiguration classes: exported components, deep links, App Links, backup/debug flags, task hijacking conditions, provider exposure, and cleartext/trust-anchor mistakes.",
    "Good for known API misuse patterns: insecure SSL/WebView, weak crypto choices, raw SQL, hardcoded secrets, weak storage primitives.",
    "Useful enrichment for downstream reasoning: permission mappings, API inventory, URLs/domains/emails, Firebase keys, secret candidates, trackers, and SBOM.",
    "Positive-control detection is a real advantage for Tool Prior: MobSF can report that a defensive control exists, not only that a weakness exists."
  ],
  "overall_limitations": [
    "No taint analysis, no source-to-sink chains, no call graph reasoning, and no path sensitivity.",
    "Code rule granularity is mostly file + line hit; it does not report method names, enclosing classes, or call chains.",
    "Pattern matches over JADX output can be brittle. Decompiler artifacts can create both false negatives and false positives.",
    "SQL injection, Jackson deserialization, and many WebView findings are only candidate patterns. MobSF does not prove attacker-controlled input reaches the sink.",
    "Android code scanning is aimed at `.java` and `.kt` text only. For APKs, Smali is generated but not used by the SAST rule engine.",
    "For zipped Android Studio source, `get_android_src_dir()` chooses either `app/src/main/java` or `app/src/main/kotlin`, not both. Mixed Java+Kotlin source trees can therefore be partially scanned.",
    "ICC support is shallow: MobSF understands exported components and intent metadata in the manifest, but not runtime intent construction/dispatch paths.",
    "No explicit confidence metric means downstream consumers must infer trust from detection method and category.",
    "Many manifest findings have no explicit CWE tag in the repo; mapping them requires inference outside the repository itself.",
    "Taint relevance: Medium.",
    "MobSF itself is not a taint engine.",
    "However, its outputs are useful priors and seed signals for a downstream taint or graph-guided reasoner: exported components, browsable activities, API inventory, permission mappings, URLs, potential secret constants, crypto/network APIs, and domain scopes can all help decide where deeper flow analysis should focus."
  ],
